    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 12,
    "last_activity_date" : 1643232346,
    "last_edit_date" : 1643232346,
    "creation_date" : 1490169775,
    "answer_id" : 42945860,
    "question_id" : 2066946,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>While the marked answer is correct there is a way of achieving this without exceptions. The service is returning <code>Optional&lt;T&gt;</code> of the searched object and this is mapped to <code>HttpStatus.OK</code> if found and to  404 if empty.</p>\n<pre><code>@Controller\npublic class SomeController {\n\n    @RequestMapping.....\n    public ResponseEntity&lt;Object&gt; handleCall(@PathVariable String param) {\n        return  service.find(param)\n                .map(result -&gt; new ResponseEntity&lt;&gt;(result, HttpStatus.OK))\n                .orElse(new ResponseEntity&lt;&gt;(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND));\n    }\n}\n\n@Service\npublic class Service{\n  \n    public Optional&lt;Object&gt; find(String param){\n        if(!found()){\n            return Optional.empty();\n        }\n        ...\n        return Optional.of(data); \n    }\n    \n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9352757,
      "reputation" : 497,
      "user_id" : 6941879,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/brPoe.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "AbdusSalam",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6941879/abdussalam"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1637334021,
    "last_edit_date" : 1637334021,
    "creation_date" : 1504492663,
    "answer_id" : 46029597,
    "question_id" : 2066946,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Also if you want to return 404 status from your controller all you need is to do this</p>\n<pre><code>@RequestMapping(value = &quot;/something&quot;, method = RequestMethod.POST)\n@ResponseBody\npublic HttpStatus doSomething(@RequestBody String employeeId) {\n    try {\n        return HttpStatus.OK;\n    } \n    catch (Exception ex) { \n         return HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>By doing this you will receive a 404 error in case when you want to return a 404 from your controller.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2530531,
      "reputation" : 874,
      "user_id" : 2198922,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1bfe10a3260ba0f797f374a742900a68?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "pilot",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2198922/pilot"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1523886486,
    "creation_date" : 1523886486,
    "answer_id" : 49858906,
    "question_id" : 2066946,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>This is a bit late, but if you are using <a href=\"https://projects.spring.io/spring-data-rest/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Spring Data REST</a> then there is already <code>org.springframework.data.rest.webmvc.ResourceNotFoundException</code>\nIt also uses <code>@ResponseStatus</code> annotation. There is no need to create a custom runtime exception anymore.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 9531412,
        "reputation" : 2925,
        "user_id" : 7082956,
        "user_type" : "registered",
